{{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Bown v. Gwinnett County School District |court = [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate= |ArgueYear= |DecideDate=May 6, |DecideYear=1997 |FullName=Bown v. Gwinnett County School District |citations = 112 [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/112/1464/585284/ 1464]; 65 USLW 2740; 118 Ed. Law Rep. 28; 97 FCDR 2801; 10 Fla. L. Weekly Fed. C 902 |Prior= |Subsequent=[[Certiorari]] denied by the [[United States Supreme Court]]. |Holding= |Judges=[[R. Lanier Anderson III]], [[Edward Earl Carnes]], [[Richard D. Cudahy]] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|7th Cir.]]) |Majority=Anderson |JoinMajority=a unanimous court |LawsApplied=[[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. I]] }} '''''Bown v. Gwinnett County School District''''', 112 [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] 1464 (11th Cir. 1997)<ref name="Bown">{{cite court |litigants=Bown v. Gwinnett County School District |vol=112 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1464 |pinpoint= |court=11th Cir. |date=1997 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/112/1464/585284/ |accessdate=2017-11-02 |quote=}}</ref>, refers to an [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit|Eleventh Circuit Court]] case in which the [[plaintiff]], Brian Bown, a school teacher, challenged as an unconstitutional [[Establishment Clause]] violation [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]'s law requiring a "[[Moment of silence|Moment of Quiet Reflection]]". The Court ruled that the Moment of Quiet Reflection was not unconstitutional. The [[Supreme Court of the United States]] denied [[certiorari]] for an appeal.
== Background == The State of Georgia passed the Moment of Quiet Reflection in Schools Act, which came into effect in 1994. The law did not require or endorse [[prayer]],<ref name="trojan">[http://candst.tripod.com/dawn1.htm Brockman, D. "A Moment of Silence: The Trojan Horse of Our Age."]</ref> saying that it "is not intended to be and shall not be conducted as a religious service or exercise".<ref name="trojan"/>
Public school teacher Brian Bown challenged the Act.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=XXCYV-yuqQcC&pg=PA289&lpg=PA289&dq=bown+v+gwinnett&source=web&ots=5Zwwtv2MaE&sig=_8NHMmNC2WcbEoi2UjyBPxWIbaA Fontana, V. "Municipal Liability: Law and Practice," pg. 289].</ref> He sued the [[Gwinnett County School District]], alleging that the law was an [[Establishment Clause]] violation implicitly requiring school prayer.<ref name="trojan"/> At trial, the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia]] ruled that the Act did not violate the establishment clause.<ref>Larry R. Thaxton, [https://kb.osu.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/1811/64872/OSLJ_V57N4_1399.pdf ''Silence Begets Religion:'' Bown v. Gwinnett County School District ''and the Unconstitutionality of Moments of Silence in Public Schools''], 57 {{smallcaps|Ohio St. L.J. }} 1399, 1423 (1996).</ref>
== Opinion of the Court == The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit|Eleventh Circuit Court]] heard the case and ruled that the Act did not violate the [[Establishment Clause]], holding that it did not violate any of the three prongs of the [[Lemon test]].<ref name="Bown"/><ref>Joan DelFattore, [https://books.google.com/books?id=zCv28KXTHgoC&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174 {{smallcaps|The Fourth R: Conflicts Over Religion in America's Public Schools}}] 174 (2004); Mary Ellen Vales, [https://www.kentlaw.iit.edu/Documents/Academic%20Programs/7CR/v6-2/vales.pdf ''Stuck in a Moment (of Silence): The Seventh Circuit's Misapplication of the Void for Vagueness Doctrine to the Illinois Silent Reflection and Student Prayer Act''], 6 {{smallcaps|Seventh Cir. Rev.}} 429, 434-35 (2011).</ref>
