{{distinguish|Chronicle of Matthew of Edessa}}
The '''''Chronicle of Edessa''''' is a record of the history of [[Edessa]] written in the mid 6th century in [[Syriac language]].

== Description ==

The ''Chronicle of Edessa'' is generally agreed to have been written around {{CE|540-550}}.{{efn|mid 6th century {{harv|Ferguson|1999|p=267}}, {{CE|540}} {{harv|Palmer|1999|p=421}}, {{CE|550}} ({{harvnb|Schnabel|2004|p=899}}; {{harvnb|Yamauchi|1983|p=85}}). {{harvtxt|Samuel|Santiago|Thiagarajan|2008}} claim without explanation that it was written in {{CE|590}} (p. 97).}} The ''Chronicle'' primarily used old Edessan royal archives as its source, as well as some more recent church records,{{sfn|Palmer|1999|p=421}} and accordingly is thought to be historically reliable.{{sfn|Teixidor|2015|p=148}}{{sfn|Baum|Winkler|2003|p=13}}{{sfn|Yamauchi|1983|p=85}}

It is extant in only a single manuscript, ''Vatican Syriac 163''.{{sfn|Bringham Young University|2004}} This manuscript was acquired by [[Giuseppe Simone Assemani]] during a trip to the [[Near East]] from {{CE|1715-1717}} taken at the request of [[Pope Clement XI]].{{sfn|Bringham Young University|2004}}

The ''Chronicle'' begins with a record of a flood during the reign of [[Abgar VIII]] in November {{CE|201}} which damaged a Christian church building in Edessa.{{sfn|Ferguson|1999|p=267}}{{sfn|Schnabel|2004|p=899}} This is the earliest mention of a building dedicated exclusively to Christian worship,{{sfn|Myers|2010|p=35}} as well as one of few records of Christianity in Edessa at this time.{{sfn|Frenschkowski|2015|p=464}}{{sfn|Schnabel|2004|p=899}} Also, unlike other [[Syriac literature]], the ''Chronicle'' does ''not'' contain any legends of the [[Apostle Thaddeus]].{{sfn|Baum|Winkler|2003|p=13}}{{sfn|Yamauchi|1983|p=85}}

